  "game_explanation": "This game is likely to revolve around red-for-blue exchange, because dog-blue-6080 values RED most highly ($1.00) and BLUE very little ($0.20), while butterfly-blue-3807 values BLUE highly ($0.90) and still values RED moderately ($0.60). That creates strong potential gains from trade if dog gives BLUE for RED or butterfly gives RED for BLUE. Ram-purple-9443 values BLUE least ($0.10) and RED only modestly ($0.40), so ram is comparatively less attached to either private-value color and is the most natural liquidity provider when offered GREEN or when unloading RED/BLUE at favorable terms. GREEN is common value at $0.50 for everyone, so it serves as a relatively transparent medium but does not itself create hidden informational advantage. Because each player only knows their own values during play, proposals must be made under uncertainty about counterpart valuations, but the low acceptance-threshold personas suggest players may test ambitious offers and still accept any strictly profitable deal. Dog is likely to seek RED and shed BLUE or occasionally GREEN; butterfly is likely to seek BLUE aggressively but can also buy RED if priced cheaply; ram is likely to explore multiple options and accept trades that convert low-value BLUE into GREEN or favorable amounts of RED. Across three rounds, the most likely pattern is early probing, followed by clearer exploitation of revealed willingness to trade, especially once holdings update and players can infer which colors others seem eager to move.",
